documentation_plan.suggested_lod: LOD 200 (Approximate Geometry). At this conceptual/early design stage, model elements are represented as generic objects or assemblies with approximate quantities, size, shape, location, and orientation. This level is sufficient for design coordination, performance analysis, and establishing spatial requirements without committing to specific products or detailed construction information.
key_deliverables: BIM Execution Plan (BEP): A foundational document outlining project standards, roles, responsibilities, and collaboration protocols.

Federated Coordination Model: An aggregated model combining Architectural, Structural, and MEP disciplines for early-stage clash detection and spatial coordination, particularly around the central core, plant rooms, and ceiling voids.

Architectural Model (LOD 200): 3D model defining the building's massing, grid, internal space allocation (apartments, amenity areas, core), and primary architectural elements like walls, floors, curtain walling, and the green roof form.

Structural Model (LOD 200): 3D model showing the primary structural grid, columns, beams, floor slabs, core walls, and preliminary foundation zones. Used to coordinate with architectural layouts and MEP service routes.

MEP Model (LOD 200): 3D model representing the spatial requirements for major MEP components. Includes placeholder geometry for main plant (heat pumps, AHUs), primary ductwork/pipework routes, main risers, and solar panel array zones.
Site Plan: 2D drawing showing the building footprint in relation to property lines, adjacent structures, and primary access points for residents and services.

Floor Plans (Ground, Typical Upper, Roof): 2D drawings illustrating the layout of all floors, including apartment mix, circulation core, amenity spaces, plant rooms, and the 'Urban Oasis' green roof layout with recreational zones and PV arrays.
Building Elevations: 2D drawings for all primary facades, indicating the intended material palette (brick, glass, metal accents) and overall aesthetic.
Building Sections: Key 2D cross-sections showing vertical relationships between floors, ceiling void allowances for services, the central core configuration, and the green roof build-up.
Outline Architectural Specification: Document describing the design intent and quality standards for key materials and systems (e.g., facade materials, glazing performance, green roof system type).

Outline Structural Specification: Document outlining the proposed structural system (e.g., reinforced concrete frame), foundation strategy (e.g., piled), and key considerations like movement joints and coordination requirements.

Outline MEP Specification: Document detailing the performance-based requirements for mechanical, electrical, and plumbing systems, referencing regulatory compliance (UK Building Regs, London Plan), sustainability targets (BREEAM 'Excellent'), and acoustic performance criteria.
